WEBVTT

00:01.418 --> 00:03.128
Something happened that last week.

00:03.211 --> 00:05.547
-He seemed burdened.
-He was the president.

00:05.630 --> 00:07.007
And he was in my office

00:07.090 --> 00:09.467
stumbling around drunk in his bathrobe.

00:09.968 --> 00:12.303
[♪ dramatic music playing]

00:13.847 --> 00:15.890
[Xavier Collins] Take me through
Wildcat's day. Anything irregular?

00:15.974 --> 00:17.058
[Mike Garcia] He got out of his bathrobe

00:17.142 --> 00:18.268
for the first time in a week.

00:18.351 --> 00:19.436
Spent the morning making pasta.

00:19.519 --> 00:20.729
[Xavier] And that's it?

00:20.812 --> 00:22.731
[Garcia] Coffee with Sinatra
in the afternoon.

00:22.814 --> 00:25.817
You know who made her daily
happy hour appearance.

00:25.900 --> 00:27.444
Kid bailed on him for dinner.

00:27.527 --> 00:29.279
I ghosted him yesterday.

00:29.362 --> 00:32.907
I told him that I wished he was dead.

00:32.991 --> 00:36.202
-How's your dad?
-Still just a light touch of dementia.

00:36.286 --> 00:38.538
Cal! Where's my son?

00:38.621 --> 00:40.957
[Cal Bradford] [on TV] That's why
we're sending these four brave explorers

00:41.041 --> 00:42.042
into the unknown.

00:42.625 --> 00:44.502
It's not what we thought. There's life.

00:44.586 --> 00:46.254
[gunshot]

00:46.337 --> 00:48.715
And I've done some things
I think might have to do

00:48.798 --> 00:50.759
-with what happened to our guy.
-What things, man?

00:50.842 --> 00:53.428
Look, tomorrow, I'll tell you everything.
I swear to God.

00:53.511 --> 00:55.013
You think you're the only killer

00:55.096 --> 00:56.723
I brought down here just in case?

00:56.806 --> 00:58.516
You gonna send somebody for me?

00:59.142 --> 01:01.644
You better make sure it's the
biggest motherfucker you got.

01:02.353 --> 01:04.522
[choking, gasping]

01:04.606 --> 01:05.857
[body thuds]

01:05.940 --> 01:07.442
[♪ dramatic music playing]

01:16.993 --> 01:22.499
[narrator] "I had a dream,
which was not all a dream.

01:23.917 --> 01:26.294
"The bright sun was extinguished

01:26.377 --> 01:31.174
"and the stars did wander,
darkling in the eternal space.

01:32.258 --> 01:34.844
"And all hearts were chilled

01:34.928 --> 01:38.723
into a selfish prayer for light."

01:38.807 --> 01:40.350
[♪ "Here I Go Again"
by Whitesnake playing on stereo]

01:40.433 --> 01:44.104
♪ Here I go again on my own ♪

01:45.438 --> 01:49.109
♪ Going down the only
road I've ever known ♪

01:50.693 --> 01:54.489
♪ Like a drifter,
I was born to walk alone ♪

01:56.491 --> 01:58.701
-[♪ music stops]
-[CD changer whirring]

01:59.160 --> 02:00.370
You want your mix back, sir?

02:00.453 --> 02:02.705
Nah, you can keep it.
I just like making 'em.

02:03.540 --> 02:04.916
[dog barking]

02:04.999 --> 02:06.000
Thank you.

02:07.794 --> 02:10.797
[♪ bright piano music playing]

02:10.880 --> 02:13.049
[TV softly plays in background]

02:13.133 --> 02:14.467
[knocking]

02:14.968 --> 02:16.678
[Kane Bradford] Hey!

02:16.761 --> 02:17.929
What took you so long?

02:18.847 --> 02:20.515
Your pilot, your jet. You tell me.

02:20.598 --> 02:22.392
[Kane chuckles, sighs]

02:22.976 --> 02:23.977
[Cal] Ah.

02:25.228 --> 02:26.437
[Kane sighs]

02:26.521 --> 02:28.982
Have you watched this guy play?

02:30.024 --> 02:31.901
-Tiger Woods?
-Yeah.

02:31.985 --> 02:33.361
Everyone watches him play.

02:34.529 --> 02:36.781
That father did a hell of a job with him.

02:37.782 --> 02:40.201
It's possible the kid
had some natural talent, too.

02:42.370 --> 02:44.539
-Anything's possible.
-[turns off TV]

02:44.622 --> 02:47.667
-Make you a drink?
-It's 11:00 a.m.

02:47.750 --> 02:49.252
[Kane] And happy hour somewhere.

02:50.962 --> 02:52.297
[liquid pouring]

02:52.380 --> 02:55.884
Oklahoma project didn't find
a drop of goddamn oil.

02:55.967 --> 02:57.468
Eh, it happens.

02:58.052 --> 03:01.931
-[glass clinking]
-I am more bullish on North Dakota

03:02.015 --> 03:03.516
and the Bakken shale.

03:04.309 --> 03:05.310
[Cal groans]

03:05.894 --> 03:09.397
I am told that you have
barely been to the fields.

03:10.607 --> 03:12.650
Got your little birdies
delivering you intel, huh?

03:12.734 --> 03:13.860
[Kane chuckles]

03:17.530 --> 03:18.531
[glass thuds]

03:19.741 --> 03:21.451
I'm leaving the business, Dad.

03:23.995 --> 03:26.581
Drilling and hydro-fracturing
were never my speed.

03:26.664 --> 03:27.999
I want something simpler.

03:30.126 --> 03:31.336
I wanna teach high school.

03:33.004 --> 03:34.255
Hm.

03:34.756 --> 03:36.841
[laughing]

03:36.925 --> 03:39.761
[chuckling] Oh! Oh, boy.

03:41.679 --> 03:42.680
No.

03:43.681 --> 03:45.808
No, no, no.

03:45.892 --> 03:48.311
Over my dead, corroded body, Cal.

03:50.230 --> 03:53.358
I will give you one thing,
you are a shit oil man.

03:53.441 --> 03:55.693
And that is why
you're going into politics.

03:55.777 --> 03:58.529
You'll begin in Kentucky, of course.

03:58.613 --> 04:00.949
Our last name alone could get a horse

04:01.032 --> 04:02.825
with a speech impediment
elected in Kentucky.

04:02.909 --> 04:05.912
Now, you can either run
as a Democrat for the Senate

04:05.995 --> 04:07.413
or a Republican for governor.

04:07.497 --> 04:09.958
Either way, once you've served
a couple of terms,

04:10.041 --> 04:12.752
we can begin to position you
for better things.

04:15.588 --> 04:17.257
I'm not a teenager anymore.

04:17.966 --> 04:19.801
-You don't control me--
-Enough!

04:22.053 --> 04:24.097
This is what's happening, Cal.

04:24.764 --> 04:28.393
You are going to have a life,
and a big one,

04:28.977 --> 04:32.313
and one that does not include
teaching dipshit 9th graders

04:32.397 --> 04:35.400
Catcher in the Rye year after year.

04:36.192 --> 04:37.986
Now, you come from a long line of men

04:38.069 --> 04:40.071
who have lived big lives,

04:40.738 --> 04:42.323
men who have made this world

04:42.407 --> 04:44.284
more or less with their bare hands.

04:44.367 --> 04:46.911
And I am not going to watch you
piss all that away!

04:48.454 --> 04:52.375
When you leave this life,
you're going to goddamn exit it

04:52.458 --> 04:54.460
with some pride in your accomplishments,

04:54.544 --> 04:56.296
even if I have to drag you

04:56.379 --> 04:59.382
kicking and screaming
to those accomplishments!

05:01.050 --> 05:02.802
Now, you will thank me one day.

05:04.095 --> 05:07.098
And even if you don't,
your future children certainly will.

05:09.267 --> 05:11.311
Unlike you, they might just be grateful

05:11.394 --> 05:12.812
for that Bradford name.

05:16.524 --> 05:18.443
[wristband chiming]

05:22.238 --> 05:25.241
[♪ solemn music playing]

05:48.514 --> 05:51.809
[♪ solemn music playing]

05:51.893 --> 05:53.895
[clock ticking]

06:04.864 --> 06:06.074
[phone chirping]

06:08.159 --> 06:09.535
[sighs]

06:13.873 --> 06:16.125
You look nice. Grown up.

06:16.709 --> 06:19.170
And you look like you're pretending
to be an agent.

06:19.754 --> 06:22.757
They just put me on leave.
I'm still an agent.

06:22.840 --> 06:26.177
-Where's your brother?
-He's next door at Carl's with, you know.

06:27.220 --> 06:29.222
[Xavier sighs]

06:29.305 --> 06:31.182
[saw whirring]

06:38.231 --> 06:40.233
[whirring]

06:45.238 --> 06:46.280
Ready? Go!

06:46.364 --> 06:48.574
-[Carl] Yeah.
-There we go. This way.

06:48.658 --> 06:49.742
[Carl] Good, good.

06:49.826 --> 06:52.203
-She really listens to you.
-[Xavier] James.

06:52.286 --> 06:55.248
Uh, Xavier, uh, James just wanted
to come over and play with Lucy.

06:55.331 --> 06:56.499
-Just a little longer?
-Now, son.

06:56.582 --> 06:58.668
-Get your jacket, come on.
-It's okay, James.

06:58.751 --> 07:00.294
Um, it's a crazy day today at the tower.

07:00.378 --> 07:01.754
I gotta get moving myself.

07:05.133 --> 07:07.176
-You gotta be more careful, Carl.
-[James Collins] Come on!

07:07.260 --> 07:08.886
The no pets rule is pretty clear.

07:08.970 --> 07:10.680
I know. Uh, I know. I just, um...

07:10.763 --> 07:12.473
[James] Come on! Bring it back. Come on!

07:12.557 --> 07:14.684
Look how much they
love each other. [laughing]

07:14.767 --> 07:16.477
[Lucy panting, licking]

07:16.561 --> 07:18.396
Expecting a 10-year-old
to keep your secret

07:18.479 --> 07:20.231
is a real leap of faith.

07:20.314 --> 07:21.858
That street lamp they're working on?

07:21.941 --> 07:23.443
That light was not out last night.

07:23.526 --> 07:26.237
How easy would it be for them
to put a camera in there?

07:26.320 --> 07:28.364
Come on, Xavier, that's a little paranoid,
isn't it?

07:29.282 --> 07:30.283
Is it?

07:32.994 --> 07:34.245
Just be more careful.

07:34.829 --> 07:36.122
You're right. I will be.

07:37.373 --> 07:39.709
I owe you, Xavier. Anything you ever need.

07:39.792 --> 07:41.794
You know, cut your lawn, trim your hedges,

07:41.878 --> 07:43.045
sourdough starter for life,

07:43.129 --> 07:44.797
-you just say the word.
-[both chuckling]

07:44.881 --> 07:46.174
Thanks, Carl.

07:46.257 --> 07:48.968
-[church bell tolling]
-[indistinct chatter]

07:51.721 --> 07:53.306
-[beeping]
-Tower?

07:53.389 --> 07:55.433
[over radio] This is Ava
with event logistics.

07:55.516 --> 07:57.727
Is there any way we can
bring in some cloud cover?

07:57.810 --> 07:59.896
[over radio] This isn't
spring break. We need somber.

08:00.813 --> 08:01.898
Copy that.

08:02.815 --> 08:04.066
Uh, let's try this one.

08:04.692 --> 08:06.068
[bell tolling]

08:06.152 --> 08:07.653
[sky operator] [over radio] There you go.

08:07.737 --> 08:09.572
-Thank you.
-[sky operator] Tower out.

08:11.908 --> 08:14.869
When I was little, my dad would always

08:14.952 --> 08:16.996
invite me into his office
at the end of the day to--

08:17.079 --> 08:18.831
to, uh, to play a little golf.

08:20.500 --> 08:23.252
Turned out, much to his chagrin,

08:23.336 --> 08:26.172
I, uh, I wasn't exactly
the next Tiger Woods.

08:26.255 --> 08:28.257
-Um...
-[light laughter]

08:29.675 --> 08:33.054
He used to say
putting was his happy place,

08:33.137 --> 08:36.015
that his head would clear,
and that all the stress

08:36.098 --> 08:38.726
and the pressure would just fade away.

08:40.436 --> 08:44.565
And I'm sure he needed golf
down here more than ever.

08:46.067 --> 08:48.194
I mean, you know, let's face it,
he was, uh...

08:48.277 --> 08:51.572
[inhales sharply]
...he was unraveling those last few weeks.

08:51.656 --> 08:53.449
You know, some of you
might have even seen him

08:53.533 --> 08:54.867
running around in his bathrobe.

08:54.951 --> 08:56.911
[people murmuring]

08:56.994 --> 08:58.579
Yeah, those, um...

09:01.457 --> 09:03.042
Those last days were rough.

09:05.169 --> 09:08.130
My dude, I got Rocky III queued up,

09:08.214 --> 09:10.007
not to mention some popcorn
and some bourbon.

09:10.091 --> 09:11.592
-You in?
-[♪ lightly strums guitar]

09:11.676 --> 09:14.345
Little Clubber Lang, some Mr. T?

09:15.596 --> 09:17.640
We can skip right to Eye of the Tiger.
It's the best.

09:17.723 --> 09:19.892
The hero at his lowest point
gets his shit together

09:19.976 --> 09:21.644
and he kicks in some balls,
you'll love it.

09:21.727 --> 09:23.980
-What do you say?
-I'd say your taste in movies

09:24.063 --> 09:25.898
is as dated as your taste in music.

09:25.982 --> 09:28.359
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah,
save it for my biography.

09:29.485 --> 09:30.820
[kicking, stomping] Come on.

09:30.903 --> 09:32.154
Watch a classic with your old man.

09:32.238 --> 09:33.990
That biography, that--

09:34.073 --> 09:36.576
that pretty much writes itself, no?

09:37.285 --> 09:41.664
Part one, an alcoholic
daddy's boy wakes up at age 42

09:41.747 --> 09:43.499
and decides he wants to be president.

09:43.583 --> 09:46.294
Okay, spare me the whole righteous teenage
shtick, will you?

09:46.377 --> 09:49.755
Part two, following the collapse
of civilization, he, uh,

09:49.839 --> 09:51.090
he hunkers down in his mansion

09:51.173 --> 09:53.342
playing Pebble Beach in a golf simulator

09:53.426 --> 09:55.803
while a bunch of gazillionaires
stick their hands up his ass

09:55.886 --> 09:58.180
-to make his mouth move.
-Jeremy.

09:58.264 --> 09:59.807
-[door opens]
-[Kane] Get off me!

09:59.890 --> 10:02.268
Ah, keep your friggin' hands
to yourself, Junior!

10:02.351 --> 10:03.352
-[Billy Pace] Hey!
-[door slams]

10:04.395 --> 10:05.771
-[Cal] What's going on? Dad.
-It's just--

10:05.855 --> 10:07.064
I was just trying to get--

10:07.148 --> 10:08.649
-Okay, alright, it's alright.
-I'm sorry, sir.

10:08.733 --> 10:10.318
We got an alert he'd left the guest house.

10:10.401 --> 10:12.486
-We found him at the neighbors.
-Okay, I wanna go to my study!

10:12.570 --> 10:14.614
-He will not let me go to my study!
-Okay, alright.

10:14.697 --> 10:17.116
It's my study, Dad.
You live in the guest house, remember?

10:17.199 --> 10:18.576
-How did he get out?
-I have no idea.

10:18.659 --> 10:20.286
Grandpa, I'll-- I'll show you
to the study, yeah?

10:20.369 --> 10:22.038
-I just wanna get my book.
-Okay.

10:22.121 --> 10:24.290
Sniper here won't let me go to my study.

10:24.373 --> 10:26.208
Son of a bitch.

10:27.168 --> 10:28.544
It's probably time we start thinking about

10:28.628 --> 10:30.630
-putting a child lock--
-No, no, no. Not yet, man.

10:30.713 --> 10:32.423
-[Billy] Just thought if we--
-Not yet.

10:34.216 --> 10:35.217
Yes, sir.

10:36.469 --> 10:39.263
No, Jeremy. My name's Jeremy.

10:39.347 --> 10:40.640
-Not Cal.
-Huh.

10:41.349 --> 10:45.102
That's what Cal named his boy. "Jeremy."

10:45.770 --> 10:48.898
Such a limp, ineffectual name.

10:48.981 --> 10:52.109
That-- That's a kind of name for a fop,

10:52.193 --> 10:53.903
a fool, or a physicist.

10:53.986 --> 10:55.571
Not according to Pearl Jam, Dad.

10:55.655 --> 10:57.365
[Kane] Ah, that's where I put it.

11:00.117 --> 11:02.536
[Cal] Okay, Dad, you can't
leave the grounds.

11:02.620 --> 11:04.580
Are you listening?
Without telling someone.

11:04.664 --> 11:05.998
Eh, you were always weak.

11:06.082 --> 11:08.000
That's why the sniper had to do it.

11:08.918 --> 11:11.462
Why do you keep calling
him that? It's Agent Pace.

11:11.545 --> 11:13.839
And these agents aren't your babysitters,
you understand?

11:15.257 --> 11:18.010
You thought they were all
lost at sea, those four.

11:18.094 --> 11:19.303
[chuckles]

11:19.387 --> 11:21.555
And they did it
right under your nose, too.

11:21.639 --> 11:23.307
You-- You know, you were

11:23.391 --> 11:26.102
never the sharpest tool in the shed, kid.

11:26.602 --> 11:28.270
Okay, why don't we get you
back to your place?

11:28.354 --> 11:29.939
Ah, ah, ah, ah!

11:31.565 --> 11:32.817
Not my president.

11:34.318 --> 11:36.028
[chuckles]

11:36.112 --> 11:38.072
-Not mine either.
-Hey, don't be like that.

11:38.155 --> 11:39.198
Hey!

11:39.782 --> 11:41.784
I don't know what I did to piss you off.

11:41.867 --> 11:44.245
You never stood up. You never fought back.

11:44.870 --> 11:47.790
You knew what was coming
and you kept it to yourself.

11:48.791 --> 11:50.418
That makes you complicit.

11:50.501 --> 11:52.670
[♪ tense music playing]

11:52.753 --> 11:54.922
-[Cal] Okay.
-[Jeremy scoffs]

11:55.005 --> 11:57.258
You know, I-I-I really--
I can't wait to see

11:57.341 --> 12:00.136
how you hide from yourself
when the liquor finally runs out.

12:05.725 --> 12:07.727
I wish you'd died
with the rest of the world.

12:11.939 --> 12:13.566
[softly] Yeah.

12:15.151 --> 12:17.153
[♪ solemn music playing]

12:20.823 --> 12:22.241
Yeah, the man loved his golf.

12:22.324 --> 12:24.827
♪♪

12:30.875 --> 12:32.793
Hey there, Collins-es.

12:32.877 --> 12:33.878
[Xavier] Jane.

12:35.087 --> 12:38.048
Have you seen Billy today?
He hasn't answered my texts.

12:38.132 --> 12:39.300
Oh.

12:39.383 --> 12:41.594
Weird, I've been trying
to get ahold of him, too.

12:42.595 --> 12:45.514
Hey, Pres, can you take James
to Carl's, please?

12:45.598 --> 12:47.767
-Come on, Booger.
-[James] Takes one to know one.

12:47.850 --> 12:49.852
[Presley Collins] [laughing]
You're still a booger.

12:49.935 --> 12:51.228
[kids continue chattering]

12:51.312 --> 12:53.647
Something's not right.
Let's go find Billy.

12:53.731 --> 12:56.108
[♪ tense music playing]

12:56.984 --> 12:57.985
Collins.

12:59.945 --> 13:00.946
Can we have a quick word?

13:02.114 --> 13:03.115
It's about Cal.

13:03.991 --> 13:05.534
Jane, give us a minute, would you?

13:11.540 --> 13:12.792
The crime scene.

13:12.875 --> 13:14.460
I sent the DNA samples to the lab

13:14.543 --> 13:15.920
for testing a few days ago.

13:16.420 --> 13:18.964
The samples never arrived at the lab.

13:19.757 --> 13:20.758
Delayed or lost?

13:20.841 --> 13:23.677
The samples never arrived.

13:24.804 --> 13:28.808
And who is the one person with the power
to get in the way of something like that?

13:35.648 --> 13:40.861
Look, Collins, I'm big enough
to admit that you had a point.

13:42.154 --> 13:43.364
But you and me...

13:44.031 --> 13:46.659
is about as wide as my
circle of trust goes right now.

13:47.117 --> 13:49.328
Well, you were dating the murder victim,

13:49.995 --> 13:52.581
so my circle of trust
is staying put for right now.

13:54.917 --> 13:56.168
[♪ tense music continues]

13:56.252 --> 13:57.586
[sighs]

14:00.756 --> 14:01.799
[Robinson] What are you thinking about?

14:01.882 --> 14:04.760
[Cal] Eh, my old man had
a bad episode today.

14:04.844 --> 14:06.804
[♪ music fades out]

14:06.887 --> 14:08.597
You know, my dad
was one of the first people

14:08.681 --> 14:10.724
that Samantha recruited
to help build this place?

14:12.059 --> 14:14.270
He had the subsurface geologic experience.

14:14.353 --> 14:16.897
He knew how to find seams in the earth.

14:19.024 --> 14:23.571
But his biggest contribution was me.

14:23.654 --> 14:25.698
[♪ "More Than Words"
by Extreme playing on stereo]

14:25.781 --> 14:27.533
His hand-picked man in charge

14:27.616 --> 14:31.120
who could open up all
of Lady Liberty's precious resources

14:31.203 --> 14:32.496
for whatever she needed.

14:35.207 --> 14:37.418
-Can I ask you a question?
-Hm?

14:38.419 --> 14:39.545
Did you vote for me?

14:39.628 --> 14:41.213
-No.
-[groans] Oh.

14:42.798 --> 14:48.554
You came off like the spoiled
moron son of a billionaire.

14:49.555 --> 14:50.598
Don't you dare.

14:52.433 --> 14:53.559
Wow.

14:54.268 --> 14:55.728
Cal, can I be honest with you?

14:56.520 --> 14:57.813
That was sugarcoated?

14:58.814 --> 15:00.900
No matter what your father
did to get you here,

15:01.483 --> 15:03.944
you have shouldered
an unimaginable burden.

15:05.404 --> 15:07.031
This is still your presidency.

15:08.073 --> 15:09.825
You can make of it whatever you want.

15:09.909 --> 15:12.036
♪ How you feel ♪

15:12.119 --> 15:15.497
-♪ More than words... ♪
-[chuckles softly]

15:16.081 --> 15:17.249
So, you're saying if
you could do it again,

15:17.333 --> 15:18.876
you would vote for me?

15:19.335 --> 15:20.920
[laughing] I am saying

15:21.003 --> 15:23.631
that I have since discovered
you have certain...

15:24.924 --> 15:27.760
-practices and policies I quite enjoy.
-Uh-huh.

15:29.178 --> 15:32.348
-I wonder what those are.
-[both chuckle]

15:32.431 --> 15:37.269
♪ 'Cause I'd already know ♪

15:38.437 --> 15:42.775
♪ What would you do ♪

15:43.192 --> 15:47.696
♪ If my heart was torn in two? ♪

15:49.031 --> 15:50.991
Hey, does my dad have a nickname for you?

15:52.660 --> 15:54.078
-A nickname?
-Yeah.

15:55.079 --> 15:56.997
Other than the occasional condescending

15:57.081 --> 15:58.874
"sweetheart" or "darling," no.

15:59.667 --> 16:01.752
No nickname. Why?

16:02.419 --> 16:05.172
He's been calling Pace
a nickname for a while-- "Sniper."

16:05.881 --> 16:07.925
-Hm. [chuckles]
-I don't know, it's weird.

16:09.301 --> 16:10.594
Yeah.

16:10.678 --> 16:13.430
It's hard to be a sniper
in a world without real guns.

16:14.848 --> 16:16.100
God, I miss it.

16:16.183 --> 16:17.476
Yeah? What's that?

16:18.102 --> 16:19.853
-Guns.
-[Cal laughing]

16:19.937 --> 16:21.438
The weight of them, you know?

16:21.522 --> 16:22.606
-Okay.
-Not just some

16:22.690 --> 16:23.857
orange rubber taser.

16:25.693 --> 16:27.319
You really think people this powerful

16:27.403 --> 16:29.279
would actually leave themselves
defenseless?

16:29.363 --> 16:31.782
[♪ "More Than Words"
continues softly playing]

16:33.492 --> 16:34.576
What are you talking about?

16:37.705 --> 16:39.331
Yeah, I can't really talk about it.

16:40.165 --> 16:43.794
Cal, I'm the special agent in charge.

16:43.877 --> 16:46.046
If there are guns down here,
I need to know about them.

16:46.130 --> 16:48.841
-I got some work to do.
-Wait, Cal.

16:48.924 --> 16:51.510
[Cal] The aquifer's acting
up or some shit.

16:52.011 --> 16:54.013
Are you fucking serious right now?

16:55.264 --> 16:56.765
This is still an illicit affair.

16:58.475 --> 17:01.854
Cal, you do realize that-- that this is...

17:02.938 --> 17:04.023
You...

17:05.315 --> 17:06.692
This is more for me.

17:06.775 --> 17:08.193
You know that, right?

17:10.029 --> 17:11.488
I can't do this right now.

17:12.906 --> 17:16.243
♪ More than words ♪

17:16.326 --> 17:19.580
♪ Is all I ever need ♪

17:19.663 --> 17:20.873
[silence]

17:20.956 --> 17:22.958
[quiet indistinct chatter]

17:25.419 --> 17:27.629
[sighs deeply]

17:27.713 --> 17:29.715
[birdsong]

17:29.798 --> 17:32.134
[♪ tense, dramatic music playing]

17:33.677 --> 17:34.762
Billy!

17:34.845 --> 17:36.722
-Hey, man, you in there?
-Billy?

17:38.348 --> 17:39.767
[knocking]

17:40.350 --> 17:41.643
Billy, man, you there?

17:50.527 --> 17:51.570
[debris clatters]

17:51.653 --> 17:52.738
[Jane Driscoll] Billy?

17:57.367 --> 17:59.369
[Xavier breathing shakily]

17:59.661 --> 18:00.662
Hey.

18:03.749 --> 18:05.042
[softly] No, no, no, Billy.

18:05.125 --> 18:06.627
[footsteps approaching]

18:09.171 --> 18:10.172
[gasps]

18:10.255 --> 18:12.758
-Jane.
-Oh, my God.

18:12.841 --> 18:14.676
No, Jane. Jane, he's gone.

18:14.760 --> 18:17.221
-No! Billy, no!
-Listen, please--

18:18.222 --> 18:20.224
[sobbing]

18:22.810 --> 18:25.521
[♪ ominous music playing]

18:25.604 --> 18:27.898
[Jane whimpering]

18:38.784 --> 18:40.119
[Jane sobbing]

18:40.202 --> 18:44.623
Yeah, I'm, uh, A-- [sighs] Agent Collins.

18:44.706 --> 18:45.916
It's, um...

18:46.917 --> 18:49.253
[Jane continues sobbing]

18:49.336 --> 18:50.671
[Xavier sighs]

18:53.549 --> 18:55.676
I'm at the home of Agent Billy Pace.

18:56.260 --> 18:57.553
Uh, h--

18:58.887 --> 19:00.055
Agent down.

19:01.849 --> 19:03.016
Uh, h--

19:03.851 --> 19:05.018
He's dead.

19:05.102 --> 19:08.105
[♪ ominous music playing]

19:09.481 --> 19:11.483
[sighs deeply]

19:16.029 --> 19:17.281
[indistinct chatter]

19:17.364 --> 19:20.409
[Jane] [sobbing] I-- I don't understand.

19:22.077 --> 19:25.706
I was with him last night.
He-- he was maybe a little off,

19:25.789 --> 19:29.209
but... I don't know, not really himself.

19:29.293 --> 19:31.795
But he brought me a sparkler.

19:31.879 --> 19:34.047
I'm so sorry, Jane.

19:34.131 --> 19:37.259
[Jane] I mean, we argued a tiny bit,
but I don't think that that would--

19:37.342 --> 19:39.761
[sobbing] Oh God, why did he do this?

19:39.845 --> 19:42.723
-[♪ somber music playing]
-[agents chattering]

19:49.980 --> 19:50.981
[light clicks]

19:55.819 --> 19:56.987
[light clicks]

20:01.700 --> 20:03.076
[sighs]

20:04.703 --> 20:05.787
"Sniper."

20:07.581 --> 20:10.334
"Lost at sea."
What the fuck does that mean?

20:14.129 --> 20:16.673
[safe beeping]

20:20.010 --> 20:21.470
-[beeps]
-[lid whirs]

20:26.600 --> 20:27.601
[groans]

20:32.689 --> 20:35.692
[tablet chirping, chiming]

20:40.739 --> 20:43.742
[♪ suspenseful music playing]

21:00.384 --> 21:01.802
[buzzer ringing]

21:03.345 --> 21:04.471
[chiming]

21:04.554 --> 21:06.682
-[tablet alarm beeping]
-Restricted access?

21:06.765 --> 21:09.810
I've got top fucking
presidential clearance, motherfucker.

21:11.186 --> 21:12.896
[tablet alarm beeping]

21:12.980 --> 21:16.275
[♪ suspenseful music playing]

21:22.281 --> 21:23.907
[softly snoring]

21:37.796 --> 21:39.089
[softly groans]

21:50.183 --> 21:52.602
[tablet chiming]

21:55.230 --> 21:57.232
[Kane continues snoring]

21:57.983 --> 21:59.276
The fuck...?

21:59.359 --> 22:02.362
[♪ suspenseful music continues]

22:11.413 --> 22:14.499
[Susan] [on tablet] As you can see,
there's nothing left.

22:15.542 --> 22:17.502
Radiation levels are still very high.

22:18.170 --> 22:20.881
We're taking a big risk
being exposed this long.

22:23.759 --> 22:26.011
[Susan] [on recording] Are you there?
Did you hear what I said?

22:26.094 --> 22:27.679
We found someone. A woman.

22:27.763 --> 22:29.681
[Sinatra] [on recording]
Where did she come from?

22:29.765 --> 22:32.184
[Susan] We don't know.
She can only speak--

22:32.267 --> 22:33.643
I think it's Creole,

22:33.727 --> 22:35.812
but maybe someone
from the city can translate?

22:35.896 --> 22:37.230
[Sinatra] I need you to keep her there

22:37.314 --> 22:38.523
until I can speak to the others.

22:38.607 --> 22:39.858
[Susan] We can't leave her out here.

22:39.941 --> 22:41.360
We're bringing her back.

22:41.443 --> 22:43.528
[Sinatra] You're not to do that,
do you understand?

22:44.404 --> 22:45.822
That is final!

22:47.908 --> 22:50.035
-[Billy] I found them.
-[Sinatra] And?

22:50.118 --> 22:51.912
[Billy] It's like you said.
They got someone with 'em.

22:52.579 --> 22:53.663
[Sinatra] They're coming back here?

22:53.747 --> 22:55.582
[Billy] Yeah. Less than a day away.

22:58.251 --> 23:00.170
[Sinatra] Then you need to do
what we discussed.

23:02.089 --> 23:04.800
Agent Pace, take them out.

23:04.883 --> 23:07.010
That's an order. If you can't comply,

23:07.094 --> 23:09.721
I'll find someone who will,
but don't bother coming back.

23:18.814 --> 23:21.691
[♪ intense music playing]

23:53.682 --> 23:55.684
♪♪

23:58.103 --> 23:59.980
-Hello there.
-Your Honor.

24:00.063 --> 24:02.149
[clears throat] I mean, not--
uh, not Your Honor.

24:02.232 --> 24:04.526
[stammering] What is-- what is it?

24:04.609 --> 24:05.944
-Uh, Mr. President!
-Cal is fine.

24:06.027 --> 24:07.988
If I wanted to make a mixtape,
is that possible?

24:08.071 --> 24:09.906
Yeah, uh, yes, we have the...
[clearing throat]

24:09.990 --> 24:12.284
...music library. Thousands and thousands
of albums

24:12.367 --> 24:14.077
in various formats
with listening stations--

24:14.161 --> 24:15.954
Terrific, terrific. Where would that be?

24:16.997 --> 24:18.707
Straight ahead and up the stairs.

24:18.790 --> 24:19.958
Thank you very much.

24:20.041 --> 24:21.418
And great work you're doing here.

24:21.501 --> 24:23.086
The library's the jewel of the city.

24:24.296 --> 24:25.797
[indistinct chatter]

24:25.881 --> 24:26.882
[chatter stops]

24:31.011 --> 24:33.472
[♪ "Here I Go Again" by Whitesnake
playing in headphones]

24:33.555 --> 24:36.892
♪ Here I go again on my own ♪

24:38.435 --> 24:41.980
♪ Going down the only road
I've ever known ♪

24:43.523 --> 24:47.694
♪ Like a drifter,
I was born to walk alone ♪

24:50.280 --> 24:52.866
♪ And I've made up my mind ♪

24:54.993 --> 24:57.787
♪ I ain't wasting no more time ♪

25:00.123 --> 25:03.502
♪ I'm just another heart
in need of rescue ♪

25:05.754 --> 25:08.423
♪ Waiting on love's sweet charity ♪

25:11.218 --> 25:14.304
Does patient-doctor confidentiality
still exist down here?

25:15.013 --> 25:16.264
Of course, yes.

25:17.933 --> 25:21.686
Confidentially, then,
if ever, for some reason...

25:22.938 --> 25:25.482
we can't talk anymore 'cause I'm, uh...

25:26.650 --> 25:27.984
let's just say unavailable...

25:30.737 --> 25:32.322
you're gonna wanna look at someone.

25:37.244 --> 25:39.079
-I-- I don't...
-Out of everyone on my detail,

25:39.162 --> 25:41.164
Xavier Collins is the only one
I really trust.

25:42.165 --> 25:43.875
So, you're gonna
want to discuss it with him.

25:46.586 --> 25:50.257
♪ To walk along
the lonely street of dreams ♪

25:51.675 --> 25:55.512
-♪ And here I go again on my own ♪
-[Cal whistling melody]

25:56.930 --> 26:00.767
♪ Going down the only
road I've ever known ♪

26:02.394 --> 26:06.064
♪ Like a drifter,
I was born to walk alone ♪

26:08.650 --> 26:11.486
♪ And I've made up my mind ♪

26:13.822 --> 26:16.199
♪ I ain't wasting no more time ♪

26:16.283 --> 26:18.535
[Sinatra] It's nice to see you
out of your bathrobe, Cal.

26:18.618 --> 26:21.705
-[♪ music fading]
-♪ Here I go again on my own... ♪

26:22.747 --> 26:24.374
I know what you did, Samantha.

26:28.003 --> 26:31.631
I accessed the files about the expedition.

26:35.010 --> 26:37.012
[birdsong]

26:42.100 --> 26:45.353
A decision had to be made, and I made it.

26:46.354 --> 26:48.982
-To be a murderer?
-Every indication

26:49.065 --> 26:52.319
is that the surface
of the planet is uninhabitable.

26:52.402 --> 26:56.489
People need to know
that there are survivors,

26:56.573 --> 26:58.742
that their people could be alive up there.

26:58.825 --> 26:59.909
And then what?

27:01.453 --> 27:04.289
They go searching, whatever the fuck
that looks like,

27:04.372 --> 27:05.832
letting others know where we are?

27:05.915 --> 27:08.585
-It's a death sentence.
-That's their decision.

27:08.668 --> 27:09.878
Not yours.

27:11.546 --> 27:13.506
-And I'm gonna tell 'em the truth.
-No, you're not.

27:13.590 --> 27:14.966
I'm the president!

27:15.634 --> 27:18.053
Don't you ever fucking
tell me what I can or cannot do,

27:18.136 --> 27:19.346
you understand me?

27:20.847 --> 27:22.432
-If I decide to tell--
-What?

27:23.642 --> 27:24.809
Say it to my face.

27:28.480 --> 27:32.984
I wanna see what it looks like
when you have balls... sir.

27:34.778 --> 27:36.946
[♪ tense, ominous music playing]

27:39.741 --> 27:41.159
It's fine.

27:42.827 --> 27:44.204
We're fine.

27:44.287 --> 27:47.290
♪♪

27:52.170 --> 27:56.007
[♪ "Make Believe World" by Sandy Szigeti
playing softly in bar]

27:57.342 --> 28:00.261
♪ The wind is blowing ♪

28:00.345 --> 28:04.099
♪ Against my face ♪

28:05.684 --> 28:08.603
♪ Sun's beating down ♪

28:08.687 --> 28:12.273
♪ With its warm rays ♪

28:13.817 --> 28:15.694
♪ The robin's song... ♪

28:15.777 --> 28:16.986
[Robinson sighs]

28:18.571 --> 28:20.073
Pace took a dose of fentanyl

28:20.156 --> 28:22.117
no one could mistake for recreational.

28:24.369 --> 28:25.787
Coroner's ruling it a suicide.

28:25.870 --> 28:29.249
Billy was trying to warn me.
He knew something.

28:30.875 --> 28:31.960
About her.

28:34.003 --> 28:36.631
So, first Cal, then Billy.

28:37.674 --> 28:38.758
It was her.

28:41.261 --> 28:43.054
-[Robinson] Tequila, neat.
-Okay.

28:45.640 --> 28:48.935
He was like a little brother to me. Billy.

28:50.812 --> 28:53.982
I was in love with him. Cal.

28:55.233 --> 28:58.820
♪ A sound so sweet ♪

28:59.487 --> 29:00.780
-Neat.
-[glass thuds]

29:00.864 --> 29:04.784
♪ And all my cares just disappear... ♪

29:04.868 --> 29:07.912
So, what are we gonna do?
Sit here and drink our feelings?

29:08.913 --> 29:10.165
That's an option.

29:14.544 --> 29:17.505
Or... we take her down.

29:20.550 --> 29:23.928
It's gonna be hard taking
anybody down without weapons.

29:29.142 --> 29:30.268
There are weapons.

29:32.645 --> 29:33.938
And I know how to get 'em.

29:34.439 --> 29:37.442
[♪ dramatic music playing]

29:52.040 --> 29:53.041
[footsteps]

29:54.751 --> 29:56.836
[knocking]

29:56.920 --> 29:58.379
I've been looking everywhere for you.

29:59.380 --> 30:00.590
How was my eulogy?

30:02.258 --> 30:03.802
Um...

30:03.885 --> 30:06.513
It... it killed.

30:12.310 --> 30:14.437
All he wanted those last few days

30:14.521 --> 30:16.731
was to hit shots with me

30:16.815 --> 30:18.483
in this stupid thing.

30:19.901 --> 30:21.611
To pretend we were playing

30:21.694 --> 30:23.738
Pebble Beach or Kapalua, and that...

30:24.781 --> 30:26.741
none of this had ever happened.

30:29.702 --> 30:31.329
I was so awful to him.

30:33.122 --> 30:34.833
I didn't even show up
for dinner that night.

30:36.167 --> 30:38.253
[phone chirps, buzzing]

30:48.638 --> 30:49.889
[phone chirps]

30:51.850 --> 30:55.103
[♪ somber music playing]

31:11.411 --> 31:13.121
How about you show me Kapalua?

31:23.923 --> 31:26.801
-[game chiming]
-[graphics whooshing]

31:26.885 --> 31:29.053
[game menu beeping]

31:31.806 --> 31:34.434
-[♪ bright guitar music playing]
-[ocean waves crashing]

31:36.978 --> 31:38.187
[chuckles]

31:39.188 --> 31:40.523
[chuckles softly]

31:40.607 --> 31:42.609
[sea birds calling]

31:44.611 --> 31:46.237
Are you-- are you okay?

31:46.321 --> 31:49.616
-Do you want me to turn it off?
-No. No.

31:50.658 --> 31:53.578
It's... it's just really beautiful.

31:54.787 --> 31:56.789
-[sea birds calling]
-[waves softly crashing]

32:05.590 --> 32:06.758
-[Kane] What are you doing here?
-[both gasp]

32:07.717 --> 32:09.302
[sighs] Grandpa.

32:09.385 --> 32:11.596
Um... I'm so sorry.

32:11.679 --> 32:13.932
Whoa, whoa, whoa. What are you doing here?

32:14.015 --> 32:16.476
-Alright, come on, Grandpa.
-Oh, I know you!

32:16.559 --> 32:17.936
No, I saw her, Cal!

32:18.019 --> 32:19.520
-You're confused.
-I know you, girl! I know you!

32:19.604 --> 32:20.855
-Whoa, hey! Grandpa, stop that!
-[Presley] Hey! Ow!

32:20.939 --> 32:22.190
-[Kane] Cal!
-Hey, let go!

32:22.273 --> 32:23.983
-Let go of me, you son of a bitch!
-Stop! Stop.

32:24.067 --> 32:26.027
-I gotta get outta here.
-What are you...

32:26.110 --> 32:27.862
[♪ tense, ominous music playing]

32:27.946 --> 32:30.365
Presley! Pres, I'm sorry. He's--

32:30.448 --> 32:32.617
He thinks that I'm my dad, and--

32:32.700 --> 32:34.410
Pre-- Pres, I...

32:38.456 --> 32:41.793
[♪ bright music playing]

32:51.970 --> 32:52.971
[phone chirps]

33:17.912 --> 33:19.330
[Cal sighs]

33:26.295 --> 33:28.548
I don't want any more of your trinkets.

33:30.925 --> 33:33.344
What? What are you talking about?

33:34.679 --> 33:36.014
I can't do this, Cal.

33:36.973 --> 33:39.183
I can't keep coming over here
like your hooker.

33:39.267 --> 33:40.852
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

33:41.519 --> 33:42.979
Hey, hang on, Rob...

33:43.062 --> 33:44.355
[sighs]

33:45.857 --> 33:47.734
Alright, I'm sorry. I'm sorry, listen.

33:47.817 --> 33:49.277
Will you come sit, please?

33:50.528 --> 33:52.613
-No.
-Hey.

33:55.950 --> 33:59.162
So, you're telling me
you came over here...

34:00.246 --> 34:02.123
dressed like this just to break my heart?

34:03.207 --> 34:04.792
-I gotta go.
-Okay, look. Hey.

34:05.793 --> 34:07.211
Come on, what...

34:07.295 --> 34:10.006
Get out of my way before I break your
fucking nose!

34:11.007 --> 34:12.467
Well, now you're just turning me on.

34:13.468 --> 34:14.469
Oh!

34:14.552 --> 34:16.220
Shit! Fuck!

34:16.304 --> 34:18.681
Robinson, wait! Hey, hey! The guns!

34:22.685 --> 34:24.312
You said you missed holding a gun.

34:25.438 --> 34:26.731
I was gonna take you shooting.

34:27.690 --> 34:30.026
The sub-basement of the arena, okay?

34:30.109 --> 34:31.652
You just punch in a four-digit code.

34:31.736 --> 34:33.237
It's my inauguration day.

34:34.655 --> 34:37.325
Are you actually trying to use guns

34:37.408 --> 34:38.743
to bribe me into staying?

34:39.827 --> 34:42.330
Yeah. Yes, yes, I am.

34:42.413 --> 34:44.290
That's exactly what I'm doing.
I'll do whatever it takes.

34:44.874 --> 34:46.709
I got a few months left on this job,

34:46.793 --> 34:49.253
then I can stop the play-acting
with Jessica. And...

34:49.337 --> 34:51.255
we can get a divorce, and you and I can...

34:52.507 --> 34:54.008
do all that romantic shit together.

34:54.092 --> 34:55.134
We can hold hands in public

34:55.218 --> 34:57.095
and talk about our love languages.

34:57.178 --> 34:58.930
All of it. I want all of it with you.

35:00.014 --> 35:01.140
Nicole.

35:02.892 --> 35:04.102
I love you.

35:05.353 --> 35:06.687
You make me crazy.

35:16.864 --> 35:18.282
Call me when you're sober.

35:28.668 --> 35:29.752
[door closes]

35:35.258 --> 35:37.593
"Cities were consumed...

35:39.679 --> 35:44.433
"and men were gathered
round their blazing homes

35:45.143 --> 35:49.105
to look once more into each other's face."

35:51.315 --> 35:54.110
[Kane chuckles, sighs]

35:55.987 --> 35:59.448
I averaged two books a week
for my entire life,

35:59.532 --> 36:02.910
and now, all I can read is poetry.

36:03.911 --> 36:08.124
It's the only thing that'll stay
in my brain from

36:08.207 --> 36:09.458
start to finish.

36:11.961 --> 36:13.004
Hm.

36:14.463 --> 36:19.260
My wife, she was an
English teacher. High school.

36:19.343 --> 36:21.512
She loved teaching this poem.

36:22.680 --> 36:25.641
Darkness. Lord Byron.

36:27.393 --> 36:29.729
My wife said it was one of the few poems

36:29.812 --> 36:32.648
that actually got her kids
to sit up in their seats.

36:32.732 --> 36:34.483
-[chuckles]
-I remember.

36:34.567 --> 36:35.568
[Kane] Yeah.

36:36.736 --> 36:39.780
I remember her giving you
that bookmark for Christmas.

36:39.864 --> 36:41.282
All the luxuries we had,

36:41.365 --> 36:43.743
and that's the one thing
you held onto all this time.

36:43.826 --> 36:44.994
[chuckles] Yeah.

36:46.162 --> 36:48.372
-Yeah.
-Kinda makes you think, doesn't it?

36:50.208 --> 36:52.210
What would she thought of all this?

36:57.632 --> 37:00.718
She would be grateful
that her son was alive.

37:02.136 --> 37:03.179
Mm.

37:05.973 --> 37:07.683
She and I met in college.

37:08.976 --> 37:10.978
My family didn't approve of her,

37:11.062 --> 37:13.356
and hers could not make
head or tails of me.

37:13.940 --> 37:17.068
So, our courtship had to be a secret.

37:17.151 --> 37:18.694
And this was our little signal, you see?

37:18.778 --> 37:20.529
'Cause I would-- I would slip flowers

37:20.613 --> 37:22.990
into whatever she was reading
so that I could be sure

37:23.074 --> 37:27.411
that she knew as soon as we graduated

37:27.495 --> 37:30.998
and I-- and I found my--
my place in the business,

37:31.082 --> 37:32.708
that I would marry her.

37:34.877 --> 37:37.713
Every flower was a secret.

37:38.881 --> 37:41.342
And then, when it came time

37:41.425 --> 37:44.887
to build the biggest secret of all,

37:44.971 --> 37:49.183
the great secret that would
carry on the history of mankind,

37:49.267 --> 37:53.145
I kept this symbol alive for her.

37:54.522 --> 37:58.526
So, when you ask, what would she think,

37:58.609 --> 38:01.529
I, I, I think that you have
confused yourself...

38:02.738 --> 38:04.782
about why I did this.

38:09.954 --> 38:12.790
I built this for you and for Jeremy.

38:15.042 --> 38:16.335
And I built it for her.

38:25.219 --> 38:26.887
Can I ask you something, Dad?

38:27.555 --> 38:29.682
'Cause I may be in a bit
of danger right now,

38:29.765 --> 38:31.017
and I need to know.

38:33.936 --> 38:36.230
I did everything
you asked of me in this life.

38:38.399 --> 38:40.234
My life was your chess piece.

38:41.444 --> 38:42.528
And I delivered.

38:44.322 --> 38:46.324
I led as big a life as a man can live,

38:46.407 --> 38:48.117
and I hated every fucking moment of it.

38:49.702 --> 38:50.911
But I did it.

38:52.705 --> 38:53.706
For you.

38:56.250 --> 38:57.501
So, does any of it...

39:02.340 --> 39:03.966
Have I ever made you proud?

39:10.181 --> 39:12.933
You never did anything
I didn't do for you.

39:14.560 --> 39:16.562
[pages rustling]

39:21.442 --> 39:25.988
"And the crowd was famished by degrees..."

39:28.491 --> 39:31.494
[♪ bright music playing]

39:45.174 --> 39:46.175
[sighs]

40:12.201 --> 40:14.453
[♪ tense, mysterious music playing]

40:40.813 --> 40:43.941
[♪ ominous music playing]

40:45.067 --> 40:47.069
[streetlight buzzing]

40:53.951 --> 40:55.619
-Dad, there's a thing I need--
-Hey, listen.

40:55.703 --> 40:59.081
Um, there's something awful
I need to tell you.

41:01.333 --> 41:02.710
I don't even know--

41:04.253 --> 41:06.005
Uncle Billy, he's gone.

41:06.797 --> 41:07.882
He's dead.

41:07.965 --> 41:09.341
[insects chirring]

41:10.759 --> 41:13.304
-What?
-I hate to drop it on you like that,

41:13.387 --> 41:15.848
but, um, there's something
I gotta take care of,

41:15.931 --> 41:18.601
and I need you to do exactly what I ask
right now, okay?

41:19.226 --> 41:21.937
Go upstairs and get
your brother, pack a bag,

41:22.021 --> 41:24.440
-whatever you can put into a backpack.
-Why, what's happening?

41:24.523 --> 41:27.359
Extra clothes, James' toothbrush,
maybe a few books to read.

41:27.443 --> 41:28.694
Dad, what are you talking about?

41:28.777 --> 41:30.738
'Cause I need your help, Presley.

41:31.489 --> 41:32.573
I need you to be in control,

41:32.656 --> 41:34.408
and I need you to be strong, okay?

41:35.618 --> 41:37.620
[breathing shakily]

41:39.163 --> 41:41.415
Uncle Billy's gone? Like, this is real?

41:41.499 --> 41:43.000
-[sniffling]
-Yeah, come here.

41:47.505 --> 41:48.589
I know, baby.

41:49.173 --> 41:50.174
I love you.

41:50.257 --> 41:52.009
And I'm asking a lot of you.

41:52.092 --> 41:53.511
I know, I wouldn't put you through this--

41:53.594 --> 41:55.554
It's okay. [sniffles] Dad, go.

41:57.306 --> 41:58.682
Do what you have to do.

42:01.227 --> 42:04.230
[♪ bright music playing]

42:04.313 --> 42:05.523
[softly] Okay.

42:11.779 --> 42:13.781
[knocking]

42:15.783 --> 42:16.784
[Xavier sighs]

42:19.954 --> 42:21.121
Hey, Carl.

42:21.789 --> 42:23.123
I need to call in that favor.

42:23.832 --> 42:26.418
It's gonna be a bit more
than a sourdough starter.

42:35.719 --> 42:37.346
What the hell is wrong with you, huh?

42:37.429 --> 42:38.597
Why did you do that?

42:38.681 --> 42:40.599
Grandpa, you scared the shit out of her!

42:42.226 --> 42:43.227
Who?

42:43.811 --> 42:44.812
Don't play it like that.

42:44.895 --> 42:46.272
I'm not playing it like anything, Cal.

42:46.355 --> 42:47.856
I'm not my fucking dad! O--

42:48.607 --> 42:50.526
[inhales sharply]

42:50.943 --> 42:52.820
[sighs deeply]

42:54.530 --> 42:55.614
Never mind.

42:57.157 --> 42:58.576
You were right the other night.

43:01.495 --> 43:02.830
You were right, Cal.

43:09.128 --> 43:10.296
What was I right about?

43:10.379 --> 43:11.547
All of it.

43:14.550 --> 43:15.551
All of it.

43:18.178 --> 43:19.430
[chuckles]

43:23.601 --> 43:25.978
Your mother wanted to name you Arthur,

43:26.562 --> 43:27.813
after her grandfather.

43:29.857 --> 43:31.525
"Too soft," I said.

43:32.776 --> 43:35.404
Not-- not a great man's name.

43:35.487 --> 43:38.657
But Cal Bradford, now, that's a...

43:39.658 --> 43:43.203
that's a name for a leader,
a leader of men.

43:49.293 --> 43:54.506
I am not proud of anything I did.

43:59.178 --> 44:04.767
But I am so very proud of you.

44:11.523 --> 44:18.364
And I am so very sorry, Son.

44:26.705 --> 44:27.956
I'm sorry too, Dad.

44:38.133 --> 44:39.635
I'm sorry for what I said to you.

44:42.805 --> 44:45.057
I forgive you for everything.

44:45.140 --> 44:46.266
[Kane whimpers]

44:50.187 --> 44:51.563
[clearing throat]

45:00.406 --> 45:02.116
[whimpering]

45:03.367 --> 45:06.662
-[thunder cracking]
-[Kane] "The world was void.

45:06.745 --> 45:11.500
"The populace and the powerful
was a lump, seasonless,

45:11.583 --> 45:16.130
"herbless, treeless, manless, lifeless.

45:16.213 --> 45:21.301
"A lump of death, a chaos of hard clay.

45:23.011 --> 45:27.307
"Ships, sailor-less,
lay rotting on the sea...

45:28.100 --> 45:31.145
"and their masts fell down piecemeal.

45:32.521 --> 45:33.772
"As they dropped...

45:34.815 --> 45:39.027
"they slept on the abyss
without waves were dead.

45:40.028 --> 45:42.740
"The tides were in their grave.

45:43.991 --> 45:48.579
"The moon, their mistress,
had expired before.

45:50.080 --> 45:54.585
"The winds were withered
in the stagnant air...

45:55.878 --> 45:58.547
"and the clouds perished.

45:59.840 --> 46:03.677
"Darkness had no need of aid from them.

46:05.220 --> 46:08.724
She was the universe."

46:14.188 --> 46:15.397
She...

46:18.984 --> 46:20.736
I saw her that night.

46:25.365 --> 46:26.492
I saw her.

